pr_review_comment_body:
Yes but it will required to generate correct inclusion like:

```
#include <lala.h>
#include <lolo.h>
#include <lala_impl.h>
#include <lolo_impl.h>
```
in the Pythran generated file but it can't be done until all the xxxx_impl.hpp file are created. So for now, I include them here and once all of the xxx_impl.hpp files exists, I will generated correct include directives.
I can do all of this in a same PR but it means no modification can be done until the end of this PR...

Ended up also taking a stab at an alternate implementation of this.

```python
EXP = tuple(reversed(tuple(2**i for i in range(8))))


@apply_to_return_value(bytes)
def alt_encode_to_bin(value):
    for char in value:
        for exp in EXP:
            if char & exp:
                yield True
            else:
                yield False
```

Benchmarking suggests it's 5-20% faster than the current implementation and I think it's a bit easier to read as well.

You should not catch the exception.
Use try {
} finally {
}

I see myself arguing about something that there should be no discussion.
We use delete in otInstnace that is statically allocated. Further, otInstance does not define any specific destructor, thus there is no need to make any delete calls at all.
@nibanks please specify a case where Windows would need to call delete on a statically allocated memory without destructor. If there is a case, I will apply appropriate changes, otherwise, we should remove all delete calls and especially remote delete implementations from a file used across all platforms.
